Macedonia referendum on name change
Macedonia's population voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether the country's name should be changed to "Republic of North Macedonia," which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has hindered the country's attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia, claiming that the name of its northern neighbour is a requirement on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the name change would undermine Macedonia’s Slavic majority identity.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts as to whether the minimum participation rate of 50% required for the referendum to be valid will be reached.
The question on the ballot paper in the referendum is: "Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth changing the name if it allows Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia split, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for the youth of Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the outcome for it to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority of the parliament.
According to the state election commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66% of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko vote in the referendum in Macedonia on the country’s name change, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, arranged a small stage and place out chairs in front of the tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don’t welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, like China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration.”
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership of NATO would lead to much-needed investment in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
“I think the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
He said a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Survey, between 30 and 43 percent of voters were planning to vote in the referendum, which falls below the minimum participation required.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of participants were planning to vote on Sunday.
70% of them voted yes.
For the referendum to be counted, 50% of registered voters plus one vote must be counted.
If the referendum fails, it will be the first serious setback to the Western-oriented government’s policy since it took over in May last year.
