John Edward: Language Skills Essential for Global Citizens
Scotland’s independent schools maintain outstanding academic achievements and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding exam results, which are only strengthened by individual and collective progress in sports, arts, music and other community engagements.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, the schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen careers and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement customized curriculums, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and in demand topics in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved scores in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received an A in the Higher Grade final exam.
Data collected from SCIS 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students studying Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subject choices are now considered as important as science, technology, engineering, and mathematics on curricula in independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that employers found it difficult for various reasons to fill their vacancies, with 17% attributed to a lack of language skills.
Having said that, language skills are becoming all the more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills are becoming necessary in a globalised world.
Regardless of their career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adult Britons published by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent said they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and with French being the only language that totaled a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
That is why it is so important to invest in language teaching for our children.
Being able to speak several languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding a meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and bring them the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly language that continues to be decisive for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
