North Korea says it will "never" disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened their mistrust of the United States and it was not possible for the country to give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that over the past year, North Korea had taken “significant steps to show its goodwill,” such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and pledging not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no chance that we unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a nuclear-related approach that would result in North Korea being rewarded for taking gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution altogether as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work towards “denuclearization on the Korean peninsula” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also declined negotiations to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘decommissioning first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even objects to the ‘declaration to end the war’,” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream come true for those people who lack knowledge about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a stalemate.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the US mainland by rockets was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocketman” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take measures for disarmament, but it said that much work remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timeframe for this, saying "whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and unfailingly until we realize a complete, final, verified disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously reinforced sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri in connection with the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
