North Korea promised a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear power complex if the United States took “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and moving toward normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Course on Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all graduate students to improve their sleep habits in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeinated “days.”
An academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often clueless about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why don't I know this until now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organized for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a range of interactive tasks.
Part of the course includes a picture of a dorm, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior directly.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know about the health benefits of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in being “adult” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in a state of starvation and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has taken one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar program of study before they begin their studies at the high-performing department.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn around the clock, leading to sleeping problems.
