HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14% in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people have been affected in the country, health authorities say.
Around 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases were transmitted through sex and marked a change from previous years.
Traditionally, HIV spreads rapidly through some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people infected with HIV in this way had been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 from year to year.
HIV transmission through intercourse is an urgent issue in China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
Because of the country’s conservative values, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will sooner or later marry women.
Many of the cases of infection are due to insufficient protection during sexual intercourse in these relationships.
The Chinese government has been promising universal access to HIV medicine since 2003 as part of its efforts to address the problem.
