Johnny English Strikes Again - Powerless Spy Parody by Rowan Atkinson
It’s now tradition to look for Brexit meanings in every new film with British slope, and the same seems to apply to this remake of the latest Johnny English action comedy – a series of spy parodies that kicked off in 2003 with Johnny English and gained new life in 2011 with Johnny English Reborn.
Will sharp satire about how obviously bad we are become the nation’s new export commodity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English with the rubber face has his license to crap to sake renewed for the second time - his name signals more than anything else that he is a wide comic creation intended for cinema audiences even in non-English speaking countries
Of course, he’s the weird secret agent, who despite his bizarre claims of smoothie glamour has got a little bit of Clouseau, a bit of Mr Bean and a measure of the guy from the opening ceremony to the 2012 Olympics in London.
He is also originally based on the traveler and international mysterious man that Atkinson once played in the now-forgotten Barclaycard TV ads that wreak havoc wherever he goes.
There are one or two great moments in the latest JE movie
I loved when Johnny English approached a helicopter dressed in a medieval armor and when the rotor blades briefly hit his helmet.
Atkinson's talent for physical comedy appears, but the humor feels rather low-key and strangely redundant, especially since the "serious" film brands like 007 and Mission Impossible themselves now offer comedy as an ingredient.
