The constant topic now is that the UK is in serious trouble.
A cyber-hacker has infiltrated Britain's super-secret web network of spies, revealing the identities of all Britain's agents out in the field, to the agent in the service's great dissatisfaction - an incredibly small role for Kevin Eldon.
It will be the last straw for a prime minister who is a pompous and hard-working figure, already suffering a complete collapse of his political popularity: Emma Thompson is doing her very best with this quasi-Teresa-May character but the script offers little to work with.
Her intelligence advisers inform her that when every single active spy is busy, she must use someone who has retired.
And that means the stammering Johnny English in person, now employed as a teacher in some wealthy institution, but offering unofficial lessons in the art of working undercover alongside.
English was sent back to Whitehall for an emergency meeting and reunited with his former long-standing sidekick Bough, again played by Ben Miller.
Bough is now married to a submarine captain, a jolly-hockey-sticks-roll where Vicki Pepperdine is close to wasted.
So Batman and Robin are back after everything went so terribly wrong at Her Majesty's Secret Service and encounter Olga Kurylenko's beautiful femme fatale Ophelia Bulletova.
Meanwhile, the prime minister will fall hard for the charismatic tech billionaire, who claims he can solve Britain’s computer trouble: the unhappy Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their odyssey of farcical pranks: dressed as waiters, they set fire to a flashy French restaurant; they wreak havoc as they smuggle aboard Volta’s luxury yacht; and English unleashes sheer anarchy as he tries to use a VR headset to get acquainted with the inside of Volta’s house.
There is certainly a lot of work behind the latter sequence, but despite the fact that the film is both charming and fast-paced, it has an air of children's TV around it.
Pretty moderate as a whole.
And as with the other Johnny English films, I can’t help thinking: Can’t the British film industry give Rowan Atkinson a role that matches his talent?
