This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work affecting nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
