Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have been killed in a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the city of Palu, Indonesia last Friday, officials said. The death toll is expected to rise.
Communications have been cut off, and rescue personnel have not yet been able to obtain any information from the Donggala administrative district, an area north of Palu, which is closer to the epicenter of the earthquake. The earthquake measured 7.5 on the Richter scale.
More than 16,000 people were evacuated from Palu after the disaster.
Here are some facts about Palu and Donggala, located on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Sulawesi, and is located in a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi. The city's population was estimated at 379,800 people in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami struck.
Donggala is a administrative area that stretches along more than 300 km of the northwestern coast of Sulawesi.
The administrative area, which is an administrative region under a province, had a population estimated at 299,200 in 2017.
The economic pillars of the province of Central Sulawesi are fisheries and agriculture, in particular the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the last hundred years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Management Authority.
In 1938, more than 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami hit western Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the circumpacific seismic fire ring, which is often affected by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesian Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries. 226,000 people died along the coasts of the Indian Ocean. More than half of them were in Aceh.
2005: A series of earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake struck near the city of Padang, capital of Western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake struck one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra. A tsunami of up to ten meters triggered. Dozens of villages were destroyed and around 300 people were killed.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the administrative district of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding people of the devastation of the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people were killed by buildings that collapsed.
2018: Major earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok. More than 500 people died, most of them on the northern side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings, and thousands of tourists were temporarily stranded.
